Church History

The late Marshall W. Lee, our first pastor,  was born April 1, 1886.  His father Reverend Abram Murray Lee, a slave in Virginia, was 18 years of age in 1865 when the Emancipation Proclamation was signed. Reverend Abram was 12 years of age when he saw Abraham Lincoln. He later married Agnes Ball and they had 13 children.
 
While living in Virginia during the days of the Civil War, the soldiers marched past their home as everyone hid in the cellar. When the troops had gone they went outside where his wife, Agnes Ball, picked up a gun that one of the soldiers had lost. That gun remained in the Lee family for many years and in 1998 was presented to the Conshohocken Historical Society.
 
Reverend Abram Lee moved his family from The Plains in Virginia to Conshohocken Pennsylvania in the year 1889 in search of better living conditions. He found employment as a coachman for the Alan Wood family. Later he was employed in the Alan Wood Iron Works, also known as the Alan Wood Steel Company. He became an ordained Baptist  Preacher and  one of the founders of the Galilee Baptist Church of Roxborough Philadelphia. Marshall Lee was 3 years old when his family moved to Conshohocken. He was baptized at the Galilee Baptist Church in Roxborough and later joined the Siloam Baptist Church of Norristown. He married Hannah May King, a member of the Mt. Zion A.M.E. Church of Norristown. She was the eldest daughter of Jesse and Ollie (Grimes) King from Westminister Maryland. She later joined Siloam Baptist Church of Norristown. The Reverend and Mrs. Lee were the parents of four daughters, Sara Elizabeth Herbert, Agnes White, Mary Thompson and Olive Banks. Reverend Lee was very instrumental in the Siloam building program and served as chairman. He was also chairman of the Trustee Board, teacher of the Young Peoples Class and Director of the Choir. A trained bass soloist, he loved to sing good classical sacred music and on occasionally sang with the famous Marian Anderson. It was traditional that he render the "Palms" on Palm Sunday.
 
St. Paul's Baptist Church is not a split of any church; it was started because of a need. the Alan Wood Steel Company was in need of laborers and brought in men from South Carolina. Many of there men lived in camp on the Alan Wood premises. Reverend Lee at that time was a licensed minister of the Siloam Baptist Church and a student at Temple University. The late Reverend J. F. Shepherd, pastor of the Conshohocken Presbyterian Church, on learning of these men being in Conshohocken felt that he should extend them a welcome to the community and speak to them about the Lord. He was accompanied by Reverend Lee and they went to the Schuylkill Iron Works and Alan Wood Steel Mill where these men worked. The men were very attentive to the preaching of the Word and sang many hymns. The late Walter W. Woods, a laborer in the mills who lived on Colwell Lane said to Reverend Lee after the meeting, "We should have a Baptist Church here." Reverend Lee replied "We have one colored church here and perhaps that may be sufficient for them, but if you think it is necessary to have another, go ahead." Meetings were held at the home Mrs. Demmie Hill Milton. The old James Hall  Mill in West Conshohocken was secured from the Alan Wood Steel Company to hold services. Many different ministers were invited to preach. A Reverend J. Ferrell attempted to organize a church from out of these services but failed.
 
Reverend Lee was invited to take over the work in 1924. The late Reverend Phillips the former pastor of the Balligomingo Church, and Mr. Rush Barr, a teacher of the Men's Bible Class of the Conshohocken Methodist Church, said to Reverend Lee, "You should take this work over, you can make it go.". Reverend Lee replied, "If the people want me they will let me know.". The people were scattered and Reverend Lee found four persons that first Sunday morning of March 1925, in a short time 18 to 20 persons were meeting.
 
On the first Sunday in April, Reverend Lee invited Mrs. Demmie Hill Milton, Walter Woods, Stephen Solomon and also Mrs. Mattie Smith to go with him to Norristown and join the Siloam Baptist Church and procure letters for the purpose of organizing a Baptist Church in Conshohocken. The Reverend J. B. Pratt, pastor of Siloam Baptist Church, with his deacons, were invited to the meeting. Reverend Pratt was moderator and a Baptist Mission was organized on April 29, 1925.
 
Reverend Lee was called to the pastorate. He accepted the call  and on July 7, 1925, called a council of Baptist Churches to recognize the St. Paul's Baptist Church. Fifteen delegates and eight churches were represented and the St. Paul's Baptist Church was recognized. the late Reverend P. H. Hughes, Pasor of Grace Baptist Church of Germantown, was moderator, the the late Reverend F. M. Hedgman, pastor of Calvery Baptist Churcvh Ardmore, was clerk. In November, 1925 a council of Baptist Churches was called to ordain the Reverend Lee. After an examination he was ordained to the gospel ministry.
 
 

 

 

More History To Follow...

Church History

St. Pauls Baptist Church was organized because of need.  Many African American families relocated to Conshohocken, Pennsylvania from South Carolina to find employment at the Alan Wood Steel Company.  At that time, there was not an African American Baptist Church in Conshohocken where they could worship.

 

Reverend Marshall W. Lee, a licensed minister, met with these newly relocated African American families. Reverend Lee, who lived in Conshohocken, also desired to worship locally. He was a member of Siloam Baptist Church, Norristown, Pennsylvania.  After much encouragement from a local businessman, Walter Woods, he decided to work with these families to establish an African American Baptist Church in Conshohocken.

 

Several organizational meetings were held in the James Hall Mill located in West Conshohocken.  On the first Sunday in April 1925, Reverend Lee invited Mrs. Demmie Milton, Mrs. Mattie Smith, Mr. Walter Woods and Mr. Stephen Soloman to meet with Siloam Baptist Church located in Norristown.  The meeting was held to procure letters for the purpose of organizing a Baptist Church in Conshohocken. 

 

On April 29, 1925, the St. Pauls Baptist Church was founded. In March 1926, St. Pauls Baptist Church became incorporated under Pennsylvania Law.  The main structure of the building was erected in 1927 by forty-five (45) dedicated members.  The stone for the church was donated by the Alan Wood Steel Company, Conshohocken. In 1950, the first annex where the organ now resides was completed.  In 1955, the parsonage was purchased.  Stained glass windows were donated by members in 1961.  An addition was built in 1967 which joined the church school and parsonage. In 1981, the sanctuary was renovated and a balcony was erected in the rear of the church. 

 

Reverend Marshall W. Lee served as pastor for more than 51 years. Reverend James A. Groves, Sr., served as an assistant to Reverend Lee. 

 

After receiving a call to the ministry, Reverend Groves was ordained and installed as our second pastor in 1977.  He served faithfully until his sudden passing in 1997.

 

On June 22, 1997, Reverend Leon Lowery, an associate pastor of the church, was installed as the third pastor. He served for seven years.

 

Reverend Mryna E. Graham, an associate pastor of the church, was ordained and installed as the fourth pastor in 2004.  She served faithfully until her retirement in May 2010.
